Assuming you pick up necessary sorting algorithm partition sort, merge sort etc. the key is that you have an array and you want to swap elements in the array for the sort to work. Given java is **pass by value** writing a method to which you pass array elements as score[i] and score[j] won&#39;t give you the required effect. 
Something like below won&#39;t have any effect for the caller

    Student sArr[] = ...

    swap(sArr[i], sArr[j])


You can however pass the reference to the array and indexes to be swapped, something as below

    Student sArr[] = ...

    swap(sArr, i, j);

Alternatively you can do all the swap in the same method where you implement your sorting logic no calling another swap method to move things around. hope this helps

To give you an idea of sort algorithm like shell sort with integers you&#39;ll do something as below (not the most efficient but to get you started)

    // implement findMin and then do shellsort as below
	public static void isort(int arr[]) {
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; arr.length; i++) {
			int mIndex = findMin(arr, i, arr.length);
			if (mIndex != i) {
				int temp = arr[mIndex];
				arr[mIndex] = arr[i];
				arr[i] = temp;
			}
		}
	}

